I assume you are referring to loading images faster in Flutter. One way to load images faster is to use a lower image quality or lower image resolution.

You can set the image quality using the `image` property of the `NetworkImage` widget. The value ranges from 0 to 100, with 100 being the highest quality. For example:

```dart
Image.network(
  'https://example.com/my-image.jpg',
  height: 100,
  width: 100,
  fit: BoxFit.cover,
  loadingBuilder: (context, child, loadingProgress) {
    if (loadingProgress == null) {
      return child;
    }
    return Center(
      child: CircularProgressIndicator(),
    );
  },
  errorBuilder: (context, error, stackTrace) => Icon(Icons.error),
  frameBuilder: (context, child, frame, wasSynchronouslyLoaded) {
    if (wasSynchronouslyLoaded || frame != null) {
      return child;
    }
    return Center(
      child: CircularProgressIndicator(),
    );
  },
  headers: {
    'Cache-Control': 'public, max-age=2592000',
    'Expires': DateTime.now().add(Duration(days: 30)).toString(),
  },
  filterQuality: FilterQuality.low, //use lower image quality
);
```

In the example above, the `filterQuality` property is set to `FilterQuality.low`, which sets the image to a lower quality. This can make the image load faster but with lower resolution.

If you want to reduce the resolution of the image, you can try loading a smaller version of the image or resizing the image on the server-side before sending it to the client.

Please note that reducing image quality or resolution can also affect the visual appearance of the image, so you should test different settings to find the best balance between image quality and performance.

