In this example, a custom `CustomTextSelectionControls` class is created by extending the `MaterialTextSelectionControls` class.

The `handleHorizontalArrows()` function is then overridden to move the selection by one character to the left or to the right, depending on which arrow key is pressed. This is done by calculating the new offset based on the current selection's `baseOffset` (the end of the selection furthest from the cursor) and incrementing or decrementing it by 1.

Finally, the `TextSelection.collapsed()` method is used to create a new collapsed selection (i.e. no text is selected) at the new offset, and the `TextSelectionDelegate` is updated to use this new selection.

Using this custom selection controls class, the user can now move the selection by one character at a time instead of by entire words as is the default behavior.

I apologize for the confusion in my previous response. The `TextSelectionDelegate` class does not have a `textEditingValue` setter. Instead, you can use the `TextEditingValue.copyWith` method to create a new `TextEditingValue` with the updated selection.

Here's an updated example:

```dart
TextField(
  controller: _textController,
  selectionControls: CustomTextSelectionControls(),
);

class CustomTextSelectionControls extends MaterialTextSelectionControls {
  @override
  void handleHorizontalEditingKey(TextSelectionDelegate delegate, LogicalKeyboardKey key) {
    if (key == LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowLeft) {
      final newOffset = delegate.textEditingValue.selection.baseOffset - 1;
      final newSelection = TextSelection.collapsed(offset: newOffset);
      delegate.textEditingValue = delegate.textEditingValue.copyWith(selection: newSelection);
    } else if (key == LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowRight) {
      final newOffset = delegate.textEditingValue.selection.baseOffset + 1;
      final newSelection = TextSelection.collapsed(offset: newOffset);
      delegate.textEditingValue = delegate.textEditingValue.copyWith(selection: newSelection);
    } else {
      super.handleHorizontalEditingKey(delegate, key);
    }
  }
}
```

In this updated example, the `CustomTextSelectionControls` class still extends `MaterialTextSelectionControls` but overrides the `handleHorizontalEditingKey` method.

In this method, we check if the arrow key pressed is either the left or right arrow key. If it is, we create a new `TextSelection` with the updated offset using the `TextSelection.collapsed` method. We then create a new `TextEditingValue` using the `TextEditingValue.copyWith` method with the updated selection, and assign this new value to the text editing delegate using `delegate.textEditingValue =`.

